msgctxt "GraphLiteral/2873894402"
msgid ""
"Species: Cosmophasis luxtextor\n"
"Time: Neogene\n"
"Diet: Carnivore\n"
"Temperament: Skittish\n"
"\n"
"Wild\n"
"I’ve found just the friend to get you through these low places, but you’re "
"going to need to keep an open mind. Though I guess anyone that’s made it this "
"far shouldn’t be afraid of an itsy bitsy jumping spider. Not to mention that "
"there's more to this shy little charmer than meets the eyes (all eight of "
"‘em)…\n"
"With all the horrors crawling around down here, it’s easy to see why any "
"spider might be a bit jumpy. And why it might have needed a clever new trick "
"of its own to keep the shadows at bay.\n"
"Cosmophasis seems to know when predators can be chased away by its glowing "
"webbing.That same danger-sense tells the spider to turn out the light when "
"something comes seeking it.\n"
"\n"
"Domesticated\n"
"It’s never easy to win someone over who’s had to hide their light away in "
"dark times. But once you do, you’ll have a “ride or die” angel on your "
"shoulder. Gain this spider’s trust, and Cosmophasis will help you out of "
"sticky situations and put its life in your hands for the toughest fights "
"ahead. And I mean that literally!\n"
"Your fuzzy new friend can gobble up the webbing of larger spiders to recycle "
"as ammunition. Then you can use it as a handheld web-shooter to slow down "
"incoming enemies, snatch up items from the ground, and swing around like a "
"spider-themed superhero! \n"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "GraphLiteral/482619303"
msgid ""
"Species: Dreadnoughtus recalcitrans\n"
"Time: Late Cretaceous\n"
"Diet: Herbivore\n"
"Temperament: Territorial\n"
"\n"
"Wild\n"
"Dreadnoughtus was a newly-described fossil genus in my day, named for the "
"idea that it was so large it must’ve had nothing to fear in its own time. The "
"current species does its namesake proud, and may even be able to defy the "
"Titans ruling our post-apocalyptic world.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"A big believer in picking on creatures its own size, Dreadnoughtus will "
"ignore anything smaller than a Spinosaur to focus on larger threats. It "
"absorbs the fury of incoming attacks to charge up its uncanny, Element-"
"disrupting bellow. Even then, this bruiser shows extraordinary patience, "
"waiting until the last possible moment to come roaring "
"back.\n"
"\n"
"Domesticated\n"
"Once tamed, Dreadnoughtus will gladly shoulder your heaviest artillery and "
"carry it -- and you -- into battle, on a platform big enough to earn that "
"‘dreadnought’ name. Your walking war-machine will swallow boulders (or "
"cannonballs!) to spit back up as acid-coated ammo.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"If you’re going to war with Titans, it just makes sense to recruit a titanic "
"creature with a grudge against them. Your Dreadnoughtus ally may go down "
"fighting, but not before softening up the adversary for a killing blow. Best "
"of luck, and give ‘em Hell for me!\n"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "GraphLiteral/3733177779"
msgid ""
"Species: Fasolasuchus sabulonatator \n"
" Time: Late Triassic \n"
" Diet: Carnivore \n"
" Temperament: Aggressive (Ambusher) \n"
" \n"
" Wild \n"
" This wasteland’s full of surprises, and not exactly the good kind. There’s "
"something out here that looks like Fasolasuchus, if those proto-crocs could "
"swim through sand like water… \n"
" These beasts might pop up suddenly to ambush you, or swim around you fast "
"enough to catch you in a sand-whirlpool. I can't stress enough how dangerous "
"this deathtrap can be! Plus their tails are strong enough to whip up sand to "
"blind predators and prey alike. \n"
" If you can help it, I recommend staying clear of those spikes. I think "
"they’ve got acid glands at the base of their spiny fins, and in their mouths "
"as well. Their caustic bite seems to melt through the thickest hide. \n"
" \n"
" Domesticated \n"
" One of these monster sand-swimmers would make a great mount, but good luck "
"slowing down something that can shrug off most narcotics. You could try "
"softening one up with explosives, grabbing a spike, and steering it into a "
"rock… But you’d have to be a bit mental to try. \n"
" I imagine the adrenaline junkies able to tame a Fasolasuchus would earn "
"themselves a formidable ride through these scorching sands. They seem to have "
"adapted to fighting larger prey, so I'd advise any faso-rider to steer clear "
"of packs of smaller creatures that can swarm over its defenses."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "GraphLiteral/1279054806"
msgid ""
"Species: Gigantoraptor nutritor\n"
"Time: Late Cretaceous\n"
"Diet: Omnivore\n"
"Temperament: Territorial\n"
"\n"
"Wild\n"
"Unless you’re planning to raid its nest, you shouldn’t let this creature’s "
"imposing size worry you. Gigantoraptor may be fiercely protective of its "
"brood, but it’s much more of a caregiver than a fighter.\n"
"\n"
"Don’t get me wrong -- this theropod will use its sharp claws and surprising "
"speed to defend its young when threatened. But Gigantoraptor has a soft heart "
"for young ones -- it’ll even take in the orphaned babies of rival "
"species.\n"
"\n"
"Domesticated\n"
"Now for the bad news: to my knowledge, no one’s been able to figure out how "
"to tame an adult Gigantoraptor -- its unique disposition seems resistant to "
"behavioral conditioning. However, Survivors bolder than me were able to sneak "
"into nests to win the trust of their young, and they claim that reward is "
"well worth the risk.\n"
"\n"
"Once matured to adulthood, your tamed Gigantoraptor will happily look after "
"any of your tribe’s young creatures, nurturing them and teaching them how to "
"fight. It can even use its call to help you find orphaned baby animals out in "
"the wild. If you bring those orphans home, then your Gigantoraptor will "
"happily add them to its brood.\n"
"\n"
"Gigantoraptor forms an inseparable bond with its young charges. Bring them "
"into a fight together and they will defend each other, and your tribe, far "
"more effectively than when apart."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "GraphLiteral/4255304429"
msgid ""
"Species: Ignis leoforma\n"
"Time: Unknown\n"
"Diet: Carnivore\n"
"Temperament: Aggressive\n"
"\n"
"Wild\n"
"Is Pyromane a cat that controls fire, or living fire that can make itself "
"look like a cat? It does seem to have more in common with the Phoenix from "
"that desert ARK than any lion. An author named Clarke said sufficiently "
"advanced technology would be indistinguishable from magic… I’d say that "
"whatever engineered this creature was plenty advanced.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"An unruffled Pyromane will stay at a low burn and shrink its profile. But "
"when provoked, that small cat can suddenly flare itself up into a lion-sized "
"inferno. It seems to drink in any nearby fire, using that power to cauterize "
"its own wounds and power up its arsenal of incendiary "
"attacks.\n"
"\n"
"Domesticated\n"
"I've only seen one tame Pyromane so far. Its rider seemed unbothered by the "
"beast’s flames, and beyond that immune to heat in general while mounted. She "
"claimed it could even carry her safely across a lava field. That Survivor "
"said she spent ages trying to win her cat over, before noticing it seemed "
"more sluggish in the rain.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"In its smaller form, her pet doubled as a shoulder-mounted, feline "
"flamethrower. And back at their campsite, she showed me how her pet could "
"fuel a forge and dry meat into jerky. I can definitely see why such an "
"improbable but versatile creature might have been engineered, even if I don’t "
"understand how.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "GraphLiteral/440971890"
msgid ""
"Species: Osto silvanimus\n"
"Time: Unknown\n"
"Diet: Carnivore\n"
"Temperament: Passive\n"
"\n"
"Wild\n"
"This time it feels like I’m trying to describe a supernatural entity, instead "
"of the usual living fossil. Crossing paths with Osto Silvanimus (commonly "
"called Elderclaw) is like communing with a forest’s soul. As much flora as "
"fauna, this ursine avatar seems attuned to local plant life.\n"
"\n"
"Although Elderclaw rarely attacks unprovoked, it won’t shy away from a fight. "
"It instinctively controls nearby vegetation to wrap itself in a thick tangle "
"of protective vines, while sending out roots to entangle any aggressor... "
"assuming it doesn't just knock them into a stupor with its massive paws.\n"
"\n"
"A nettled Elderclaw will conjure up a Spirit Echo to help ward off threats. "
"This ethereal talisman will then emanate vibrations that weaken threats while "
"invigorating those in its protection. A Spirit Echo collects the energies of "
"nearby violence and imbues its Elderclaw master with enough fury and power to "
"trigger explosive growth.\n"
"\n"
"While Spirit Echoes generally stay immaterial, they can also become tangible "
"long enough to explode. The resulting cloud of charged spores will affect "
"friend and foe differently, burning aggressors but closing wounds on "
"allies.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"Domesticated\n"
"While I've yet to see a tame adult Elderclaw, their cubs (or shrubs?) seem "
"much more impressionable. Sadly, this has led Survivors to hunt and kill "
"these lumbering giants for their seeds. Propagating your own is a long, "
"difficult process, but once a sproutling has grown enough to leave its "
"garden, you’ll gain a protective forest warden that can use its roots to "
"sustainably harvest nearby trees.\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "GraphLiteral/3116941109"
msgid ""
"Species: Rhyniognatha antiquagenitorTime: Early DevonianDiet: "
"OmnivoreTemperament: AggressiveWildI swear, every new creature I come across "
"here makes me more sure they’ve all had their genes tampered with. I know I'm "
"right about this! Take this monster bug I’m calling 'Rhyniognatha "
"antiquagenitor' -- big enough to headline a horror flick, but still light "
"enough to fly and skate across water.Would you believe it also makes a "
"weirdly useful, quick-hardening resin with a variety of uses? It can thicken "
"up its shell for a defensive boost, spray hard bullet-like globs, or squirt "
"soft globs that harden on impact to gum up incoming "
"predators!DomesticatedThis overgrown earwig is just what you need to level up "
"your tribe’s aerial defenses. It can stick itself to creatures or cargo and "
"carry things around your base, and its glue-bombs disrupt Tek just as well as "
"Dinopithecus dung!That said, Rhyniognatha-raising isn't for the squeamish... "
"Their males have a pheromone that invites egg-laying females to use them as "
"hosts. Harvest that pheromone, and you can mark any creature for the female "
"to lay her eggs on. The host then incubates a new generation of larvae that "
"can reap its best traits in the process.If some poor beast gets eggs laid on "
"it by accident, you might still be able to save it by popping it in a cryopod "
"and freezing out the larvae."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "GraphLiteral/2441929722"
msgid ""
"Species: Shastasaurus carmentellum\n"
"Time: Late Triassic\n"
"Diet: Carnivore\n"
"Temperament: Curious\n"
"\n"
"Wild\n"
"This odd variant of Shastasaurus seems as curious about humans as its distant "
"relative Ichthyosaur. It sure got my attention when one of these sea monsters "
"swam up to have a look at me! Luckily, its bulk turns out to be worse than "
"its bite.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"Shastasaurus has weaponized the ultrasonic chirps it uses for echolocation. "
"It can focus those sounds into a tight cone that disorients prey, or widen "
"the effect to blast apart a school of fish in a concussive "
"wave.\n"
"\n"
"Domesticated\n"
"Taming a Shastasaurus was one of the most rewarding experiences of my life. I "
"brought along some Ichthyosaur pals to entertain their larger cousin while I "
"used a sickle to clear away some of its troublesome parasites. From then on, "
"I had a gigantic escort in deep water.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"Some tribes manage to kit out their finny friend with a periscope, torpedo "
"bays, and even a cargo hold… Those Shastasaurs end up looking like something "
"from the old kids’ cartoon with cavemen who turned dinos into cars and "
"submarines!\n"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "GraphLiteral/1977359039"
msgid ""
"Species: Umbris phasmequester\n"
"Time: Unknown\n"
"Diet: Carrion Feeder\n"
"Temperament: Aggressive near carcasses\n"
"\n"
"Wild \n"
"I’d have thought an apex predator like T. Rex or Giganotosaurus would be the "
"scariest thing on the ARK, until I first saw this vision from a heavy metal "
"album cover spread its wings. Dreadmare can induce an acute threat response "
"in literally anything. All the better to scare away other scavengers from the "
"dead meat it’s drawn to.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"Those wings can focus gusts to create pressure blasts at the point of impact. "
"Dreadmare also has an uncanny way of disrupting a target’s healing abilities "
"while boosting its own. And there’s no outnumbering this terror, since its "
"dreadful aura seems to drain the will to live from everything around it. "
"\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"Domesticated\n"
"You aren’t going to break this beast the usual way. The only way to gain a "
"Dreadmare’s respect is by killing it a few times. Yes, you read that right -- "
"you will need to respawn one to fight again and again until you prove "
"yourself worthy. \n"
"\n"
"\n"
"Once you’ve won its favor, your Dreadmare will reveal its greatest ability: "
"to tuck another of your war-beasts into a pocket dimension for later access. "
"Soon you’ll be riding into battle on a shadowy pegasus that can bring along "
"surprise backup!\n"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "GraphLiteral/1604040513"
msgid ""
"Species: Yi Ling\n"
"Time: Late Jurassic\n"
"Diet: Omnivore\n"
"Temperament: Aloof\n"
"\n"
"Wild\n"
"This feathered fella is so much bigger than the Yi species I knew in my day! "
"Despite its aberrant size, Yi ling is still somehow light enough to cling to "
"walls and it can even glide short distances. It’s light on its feet as well, "
"able to dodge attacks on the run.\n"
"I’m glad Yi seems to prefer prey smaller than itself, because it can eject a "
"spray of barbed feathers at an unhappy target before darting in to rip them "
"back out. Its unique firepower may expose Yi in the short term, but its "
"protective plumage regrows fast.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"Domesticated\n"
"A tamed Yi makes for an excellent -- if precarious -- hunting mount. Some "
"tribes use them as caravan scouts, others to torment enemy forces.\n"
"I’ve seen Yi scarf up the weird mushrooms, congealed gas balls, and nameless "
"creatures scurrying around down here. Who knows what effect a diet like that "
"would have on its feathery weaponry? Watch what your Yi eats, and you just "
"might learn to sharpen its fighting skills!"
msgstr ""

